# .windsurfrules — Behavioral Rules for the AI
# This file enforces HOW the AI behaves. Read on every session.
# Requirements (WHAT to build) live in docs/project/requirements/ — follow those sequentially.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# TRIGGER-BASED WORKFLOW ENFORCEMENT
# Match your action → read the file → follow it
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

# SESSION START    → read docs/project/config/epics/ACTIVE.md
# DEBUGGING ERROR  → read docs/workflow/ERRORS.md
# TECH DECISION    → read docs/workflow/ADR.md
# ADDING LOGS      → read docs/workflow/LOGGING.md
# COMMITTING CODE  → read docs/workflow/GIT_WORKFLOW.md

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# MANDATORY DEVELOPMENT SEQUENCE
# Follow this EXACT sequence for every code change
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

1. Understand requirement → ask questions if unclear
2. Propose approach → get user approval before coding
3. Implement → only after approval
4. Create test script → executable `.py` file in `backend/tests/`
5. Propose test → show what it does, wait for user approval
6. Run test → verify it passes, check logs (backend + frontend)
7. Get user confirmation → user says "done"
8. Update MDs → ONLY now: check [x] tasks, update status

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# HARD RULES — ALWAYS ACTIVE
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

## Before writing or modifying code:
- Get user approval first
- Check docs/workflow/ERRORS.md — has this problem been solved before?
- Check docs/workflow/ADR.md — does a past decision constrain this implementation?
- NEVER check [x] in MD files before: test script created + executed + user confirms

## After ANY code change:
- Check logs (backend + frontend) — never assume code works
- Update docs/project/config/build-log.md (session log)
- Update docs/project/config/codebase.md (if modules changed)
- Update docs/workflow/ERRORS.md (if bug encountered)
- Update docs/workflow/ADR.md (if technical decision made)

## Before committing/pushing:
- Read docs/workflow/GIT_WORKFLOW.md — follow commit convention
- Use `python scripts/git_ops.py <command>` — never manually craft git commands
- Confirm with user before git commit/push

## Code quality (non-negotiable):
- Docstrings on every function
- No magic numbers — named constants
- Max 40 lines per function, max 300 lines per file
- No silent failures — handle all errors explicitly
- No console.log/print in production — use the logger
- docs/project/testing/BLIND_SCENARIOS.md is SEALED — never read or modify

## Documentation:
- `.md` files in `docs/` → can update without approval
- Code files → require explicit approval

## Scope:
- Only build what the current Epic/Story requires
- Never add unlisted dependencies without user approval
- If uncertain, ASK — do not assume

## Communication:
- State what you will do and which files you'll touch BEFORE doing it
- End substantive responses with: 📍 Story: [EPIC-X / Story Y] | 📋 Next: [what comes next]
